## 2. Hero Video — Same-Origin Download (Recommended by CEO Review)

The CEO flagged hotlinking as the #1 execution risk (CORS, hotlink protection, URL churn). **Strongly recommend downloading the MP4 into `assets/` during the build step** so the demo is fully self-contained and same-origin. Run this before finalizing the demo:

```bash
# Create assets dir
mkdir -p "../michaelwegter.com/public/demos/construction-company-website/assets"

# Download hero video (1080p — ~25MB, acceptable for a demo asset)
curl -L "https://videos.pexels.com/video-files/855271/855271-hd_1920_1080_25fps.mp4" \
  -o "../michaelwegter.com/public/demos/construction-company-website/assets/hero.mp4"

# Download hero poster (fallback image)
curl -L "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1504307651254-35680f356dfd?w=1920&q=80" \
  -o "../michaelwegter.com/public/demos/construction-company-website/assets/hero-poster.jpg"
```

Then the `<video>` tag references `assets/hero.mp4` — no CORS, no hotlink risk, always loads. The `poster` attribute references `assets/hero-poster.jpg`. The `.gitignore` for the site repo should not be excluding large binary assets in `public/` (check if needed).

If the video file is too large to commit to GitHub Pages (limit: 100MB per file, site limit 1GB), use Git LFS OR fall back to the CDN hotlink with the poster fallback. The 1080p Pexels video is ~20-30MB which is safe.

